trial by jury and who composed the jury. Oldham then considers the extensive historical use of a variety of “special juries,” such as juries of merchants for commercial cases and juries of women for claims of pregnancy. Special juries were used for centuries in both English and American law, although they are now considered antithetical to the idea that American juries should be drawn from jury pools that reflect reasonable cross-sections of their communities. An introductory overview addresses the relevance of Anglo-American legal tradition and history in understanding America's modern jury system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aJuryzEnglandxHistory. 0aJuryzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLAW / Jury.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aConstitution.  aJames.  aLegal.  aOldham.  aassembles.  aessays.  ahistorian.  ahistory.  ajury.  apreserved.  asignature.  atracing.  atransplanted.  atrial.  awork.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081476204240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814762592.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814762592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814762592/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK